        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Jan 15<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>
                    <salute>My dear Häckel</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I have been astonished by just receiving your beautiful book on corals.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> I thought you were going to publish a mere pamphlet on some new species. The drawings are the most wonderful things I ever saw in my whole life. Those of the corals excel photographs in clearness, &amp; it like having the specimens themselves well cleaned on the table. What an artist you are! I thank you heartily for this valuable present. In the course of a few days I will begin &amp; read the text.</p>
<p>You are a most wonderful man for work.</p>
<p>Yours most sincerely | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10356.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Ernst Haeckel, 13 January 1876</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD’s copy of Haeckel’s <hi rend="italic">Arabische Korallen</hi> (Arabian corals; Haeckel 1876b) is in the Darwin Library–Down. See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10356.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Ernst Haeckel, 13 January 1876</ref>.</note>
